Fishes were collected from the Clear Lake area and its tributaries with a 3m otter  trawl. A 6mm bar mesh cover was used over the cod end or the trawl during some of the sampling to capture post larval fish, many of which were less than 15mm in length. The larger bar of mesh of the trawl  19mm and 13 mm in the body and length . The larger bar of mesh of trawl, 19 mm and 13mm in the body and cod end, respectively, permitted many of the smaller fish to escape when the cover was not used.

LAB_PRES_NOTES: Trawling times varied from 10 minutes to 2 hours depending on the depth and bottom conditions. Most tows were for 30 minutes. 98 bottom trawl samples were taken in 1970, 84 in 1971, 118 in 1972. From June 1973 to January 1974, 36 trawl samples were taken in areas where a shrimp fleet was working. In June, July and August 1974, 45 samples were taken with the fleet. Trawling sampling depths ranged between 5.5 and 173.7 m. Field work was accomplished from aboard the Texas Parks and Wildlife vessel Western Gulf. An attempt was made to take samples at 9.1 m intervals each month, with supplementary sampling as time allowed. The majority of collections were obtained between 7.3 and 64.0 m off shore of Port Aransas and Freeport-Galveston.

Field work was conducted from a small outboard boat. A systematic sampling survey, consisting of several passes through the 2m wide study transect, was made on eight occasions between August, 1970 and July, 1971. Studies on food habits of the red snapper, Lutjanus campechanus (Poey), were conducted by James K. Davis concurrently with the present study.

LAB_PRES_PHYS_METH: Two 25m nets were deployed in sequence between transects. Nets were set on three successive days at 1730 then checked at 2030 and again at midnight for both crepuscular and nocturnal predators.
